  <text>
    <body>
      <div type="article" xml:id="article">

        <head>Ada Lovelace</head>

        <!--  1 LEAD -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="lead">
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace</persName>
            (née Byron;
            <date when="1815-12-10">10 December 1815</date> –
            <date when="1852-11-27">27 November 1852</date>), also known as 
            <persName ref="#ada">Ada Lovelace</persName>, was an English 
            <term ref="#math">mathematician</term> and writer chiefly known for work on
            <persName ref="#babbage">Charles Babbage</persName>'s proposed mechanical general-purpose
            <term ref="#comp">computer</term>, the
            <objectName ref="#analytical_engine">Analytical Engine</objectName>.
            She was the first to recognise the machine had applications beyond pure calculation.
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> is often considered the first
            <term ref="#comp">computer programmer</term>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 2 PARENTAGE -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="parentage">
          <head>Parentage and early life</head>
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> was the only legitimate child of
            poet <persName ref="#byron">Lord Byron</persName> and
            reformer <persName ref="#milbanke">Anne Isabella Milbanke</persName>.
            <persName ref="#byron">Lord Byron</persName> separated from his wife a month after
            <persName ref="#ada">Ada</persName> was born, and died when she was eight.
            Her mother promoted <persName ref="#ada">Ada</persName>'s interest in
            <term ref="#math">mathematics</term> and logic, in an effort to prevent her from
            developing her father's perceived insanity.
            <persName ref="#ada">Ada</persName> herself described her approach as
            <quote source="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Lovelace"><term ref="#ps">"poetical science"</term></quote>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 3 EDUCATION -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="education">
          <head>Education</head>
          <p>
            From 1832, when she was seventeen, her mathematical abilities began to emerge.
            Her educators included <persName ref="#somerville">Mary Somerville</persName>,
            the noted Scottish astronomer and mathematician, and, from 1840, the mathematician and logician
            <persName ref="#demorgan">Augustus De Morgan</persName>, who extended her
            <quote source="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Lovelace">much help in her mathematical studies</quote>,
            including study of advanced calculus topics and the
            <term ref="http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q694114">numbers of Bernoulli</term>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 4 MEETING BABBAGE -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="meeting-babbage">
          <head>Meeting Charles Babbage</head>
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> first met
            <persName ref="#babbage">Charles Babbage</persName> on
            <date when="1833-06-05">5 June 1833</date>,
            when she and her mother attended one of his Saturday night soirées
            with their mutual friend, and <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName>'s private tutor,
            <persName ref="#somerville">Mary Somerville</persName>.
            Later that month <persName ref="#babbage">Babbage</persName> invited
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> to see the prototype of his
            <objectName ref="#difference_engine">Difference Engine</objectName>;
            she became fascinated with the machine.
            Her mathematical talents led her to a long working relationship and friendship with
            <persName ref="#babbage">Babbage</persName>, and she was particularly interested in his work
            on the <objectName ref="#analytical_engine">Analytical Engine</objectName>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 5 MARRIAGE -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="marriage">
          <head>Marriage</head>
          <p>
            On <date when="1835-07-08">8 July 1835</date>,
            <persName ref="#ada">Ada</persName> married
            <persName ref="#king">William, 8th Baron King</persName>, becoming Lady King.
            In <date when="1838">1838</date> her husband was made
            <persName ref="#king">Earl of Lovelace</persName>,
            and she thereby became Countess of Lovelace.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 6 SOCIAL CIRCLE -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="social-circle">
          <head>Social circle</head>
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> moved in distinguished scientific and literary circles:
            her acquaintances included the scientist
            <persName ref="#faraday">Michael Faraday</persName> and the author
            <persName ref="#dickens">Charles Dickens</persName>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 7 TRANSLATION -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="translation">
          <head>The Menabrea translation and the Notes</head>
          <p>
            In <date when="1840">1840</date>,
            <persName ref="#babbage">Babbage</persName> was invited to give a seminar at the
            <orgName ref="#uni_turin">University of Turin</orgName> in
            <placeName ref="#turin">Turin</placeName> about his
            <objectName ref="#analytical_engine">Analytical Engine</objectName>.
            <persName ref="#menabrea">Luigi Menabrea</persName>, a young Italian engineer and the future
            Prime Minister of Italy, transcribed <persName ref="#babbage">Babbage</persName>'s lecture into French
            (<bibl ref="#menabrea_1842"><title>Notions sur la machine analytique de M. Charles Babbage</title>, <date when="1842">1842</date></bibl>).
            <persName ref="#babbage">Babbage</persName>'s friend
            <persName ref="#wheatstone">Charles Wheatstone</persName> commissioned
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> to translate
            <persName ref="#menabrea">Menabrea</persName>'s paper into English.
          </p>
          <p>
            During a nine-month period in
            <date from="1842" to="1843">1842–43</date>,
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> translated
            <persName ref="#menabrea">Menabrea</persName>'s article.
            She augmented the paper with seven notes, A to G, about three times longer than the translation.
            The translation and notes were then published in the
            <date when="1843-09">September 1843</date> edition of
            <bibl ref="#notes_1843">Taylor's <title level="j">Scientific Memoirs</title></bibl>
            under her initials AAL.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 8 NOTE G -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="note-g">
          <head>Note G and the first algorithm</head>
          <p>
            The notes are important in the early history of <term ref="#comp">computers</term>,
            especially since <bibl ref="#note_g"><title>Note G</title></bibl> described, in complete detail,
            a method for calculating a sequence of
            <term ref="http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q694114">Bernoulli numbers</term>
            using the <objectName ref="#analytical_engine">Analytical Engine</objectName>,
            which might have run correctly had it ever been built.
            Based on this work, <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> is now widely considered
            the first <term ref="#comp">computer programmer</term>, and her method has been called
            the world's first published <term ref="#comp">computer program</term>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 9 DEATH AND BURIAL -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="death">
          <head>Death and burial</head>
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName> died at the age of 36 on
            <date when="1852-11-27">27 November 1852</date>
            from cervical cancer at her home in
            <placeName ref="#london">London</placeName>. In 
            <date when="1852-08">August 1852</date>, during her final illness,
            <persName ref="#dickens">Charles Dickens</persName> visited her at her request and read to her
            a scene from his novel <title>Dombey and Son</title>.
            She was buried, at her request, next to her father at the
            <placeName ref="#hucknall_church">Church of St Mary Magdalene</placeName> in Hucknall,
            Nottinghamshire.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- 10 LEGACY -->
        <div type="section" xml:id="legacy">
          <head>Legacy</head>
          <p>
            <persName ref="#ada">Lovelace</persName>'s work has been celebrated as a foundation of
            <term ref="#comp">computer science</term>. In <date when="1980">1980</date>,
            the United States Department of Defense named a newly developed
            <term ref="#comp">programming language</term>
            <objectName ref="#ada_language">Ada</objectName> after her.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </body>
